<p><b>Yarn</b> is a long continuous length of interlocked <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibre" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fibre">fibres=
</a>, used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sewing" title=3D"Sew=
ing">sewing</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crochet" title=3D=
"Crochet">crocheting</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knitting=
" title=3D"Knitting">knitting</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Weaving" title=3D"Weaving">weaving</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Embroidery" title=3D"Embroidery">embroidery</a>, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rope" title=3D"Rope">ropemaking</a>, and the producti=
on of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Textile" title=3D"Textile">t=
extiles</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-definition_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-definition-1"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thread_(yarn)" title=3D"Thread =
(yarn)">Thread</a></i> is a type of yarn intended for sewing by hand or <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sewing_machine" title=3D"Sewing machi=
ne">machine</a>. Modern manufactured sewing threads may be finished with <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wax" title=3D"Wax">wax</a> or other =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lubricant" title=3D"Lubricant">lub=
ricants</a> to withstand the stresses involved in sewing.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite=
_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Embroidery_thr=
ead" title=3D"Embroidery thread">Embroidery threads</a> are yarns specifica=
lly designed for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Needlework" title=
=3D"Needlework">needlework</a>. Yarn can be made of a number of natural or =
synthetic materials, and comes in a variety of colors and thicknesses (refe=
rred to as "weights"). Although yarn may be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Dyeing" title=3D"Dyeing">dyed</a> different colours, most yarns a=
re solid coloured with a uniform <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H=
ue" title=3D"Hue">hue</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Etymology"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The word "<a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/yarn#English" class=
=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:yarn">yarn</a>" comes from <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_English" title=3D"Middle English">Middle English</=
a>, from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_English" title=3D=
"Old English">Old English</a> <span title=3D"Old English (ca. 450-1100)-lan=
guage text"><i lang=3D"ang">gearn</i></span>, akin to <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_High_German" title=3D"Old High German">Old High Ger=
man</a> <i><span title=3D"Old High German (ca. 750-1050)-language text"><i =
lang=3D"goh">garn</i></span></i>, "yarn", <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Dutch_language" title=3D"Dutch language">Dutch</a> <i><span title=
=3D"Dutch-language text"><i lang=3D"nl">garen</i></span></i>, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greek" title=3D"Ancient Greek">Ancient =
Greek</a> <span title=3D"Ancient Greek (to 1453)-language text"><span lang=
=3D"grc">=CF=87=CE=BF=CF=81=CE=B4=CE=AE</span></span> (<i>chord=C4=93</i>, =
"string"), and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanskrit" title=3D"=
Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a> <span title=3D"Sanskrit-language romanization"><i la=
ng=3D"sa-Latn">hira</i></span>, "band".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-definition_1-1" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note=
-definition-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> It originally referred to entrails.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#=
cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ministry_of_Information_First_World_War_Offic=
ial_Collection_Q28358.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https:=
//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/Ministry_of_Information=
_First_World_War_Official_Collection_Q28358.jpg/250px-Ministry_of_Informati=
on_First_World_War_Official_Collection_Q28358.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"250" height=3D"189" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1300" =
data-file-height=3D"982"></a><figcaption>Natural-fiber yarns used in the pr=
oduction of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rope" title=3D"Rope">r=
ope</a>, Scotland, 1918</figcaption></figure>
<p>The human production of yarn is known to have existed since the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stone_Age" title=3D"Stone Age">Stone Age<=
/a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiber" title=3D"Fiber">Fiber<=
/a> materials came from animal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hid=
e_(skin)" title=3D"Hide (skin)">hides</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Reed_(plant)" title=3D"Reed (plant)">reeds</a>, <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cotton" title=3D"Cotton">cotton</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wool" title=3D"Wool">wool</a>, and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silk" title=3D"Silk">silk</a>. Textile <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trade" title=3D"Trade">trade</a> contribu=
ted immensely to the ancient global economy.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-4"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Materials">Materials</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Materials"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Yarn can be made from a number of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Natural_fiber" title=3D"Natural fiber">natural</a> or <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synthetic_fiber" title=3D"Synthetic fiber">synthetic=
 fibers</a>, or a blend of natural and synthetic fibers.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Natural_fibers">Natural fib=
ers</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Natural fibers"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_fiber" title=
=3D"Natural fiber">Natural fiber</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Cotton">Cotton</h4><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3Dedit&a=
mp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Cotton"><span>edit</span></a><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Fl%C3%BCgelspinnmaschine.jpeg=
" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wi=
kipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Fl%C3%BCgelspinnmaschine.jpeg/250px-Fl%C3%BCgels=
pinnmaschine.jpeg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"375" class=3D=
"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1799" data-file-height=3D"2700"></a><f=
igcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cotton-spinning_machiner=
y" title=3D"Cotton-spinning machinery">Flyer spinning</a> of cotton</figcap=
tion></figure>
<p>The most common plant fiber is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Cotton" title=3D"Cotton">cotton</a>, which is typically spun into fine yarn=
 for mechanical weaving or knitting into <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Cloth" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cloth">cloth</a>.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-advameg_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-advameg-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Silk">Silk</h4><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Silk"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silk" title=3D"Silk">Silk</a> i=
s a natural <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protein" title=3D"Prot=
ein">protein</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiber" title=3D"F=
iber">fiber</a>, some forms of which can be woven into textiles. The protei=
n fiber of silk is composed mainly of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Fibroin" title=3D"Fibroin">fibroin</a> and is produced by the larvae of=
 the moth <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bombyx_mori" title=3D=
"Bombyx mori">Bombyx mori</a></i>. Silk production is thought to have begun=
 in China and silk thread and cloth manufacture was well-established by the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shang_dynasty" title=3D"Shang dyn=
asty">Shang dynasty</a> (1600=E2=80=931050 BCE).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-postrel=
_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cit=
e_note-postrel-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-silkculture_7-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-silkcultu=
re-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Linen">Linen</h4><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Linen"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linen" title=3D"Linen">Linen</a=
> is another natural fiber with a long history of use for yarn and textiles=
. Linen fibers are derived from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Flax" title=3D"Flax">flax</a> plant.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-8"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Other_plant_fibers">Other p=
lant fibers</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Yarn&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Other plant =
fibers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:40-QWSTION-BANANATEX-WARPING-LAUSCHSICHT.jpg"=
 class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wik=
ipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/40-QWSTION-BANANATEX-WARPING-LAUSCHSICHT.jpg/250p=
x-40-QWSTION-BANANATEX-WARPING-LAUSCHSICHT.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"250" height=3D"335" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"4420" dat=
a-file-height=3D"5927"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Manila_hemp" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Manila hemp">Manila hemp</=
a> warp yarns being prepared for weaving in a modern textile factory</figca=
ption></figure>
<p>Other plant fibers which can be spun include <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Bamboo" title=3D"Bamboo">bamboo</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Hemp" title=3D"Hemp">hemp</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Maize" title=3D"Maize">maize</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Urtica_dioica" title=3D"Urtica dioica">nettle</a>, and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Soy"=
>soy</a> fiber.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-vikki_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-vikki-10"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Animal_fibers">Animal fiber=
s</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Animal fibers"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The most common spun animal fiber is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Wool" title=3D"Wool">wool</a> harvested from <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Sheep" title=3D"Sheep">sheep</a>. As long fibers make bett=
er yarn, sheep have been bred over time to produce longer fibers. This incr=
eases the need for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sheep_shearing"=
 title=3D"Sheep shearing">shearing</a> to prevent pests and overheating.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-doyle_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-doyle-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Other animal fibers used include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Alpaca" title=3D"Alpaca">alpaca</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Angora_wool" title=3D"Angora wool">angora</a>, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mohair" title=3D"Mohair">mohair</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Llama" title=3D"Llama">llama</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cashmere_wool" title=3D"Cashmere wool">cashmere</a=
>, and silk.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-vikki_10-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-vikki-10"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> More rar=
ely, yarn may be spun from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camel" =
title=3D"Camel">camel</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yak" ti=
tle=3D"Yak">yak</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_brusht=
ail_possum" title=3D"Common brushtail possum">possum</a>, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Musk_ox" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Musk ox">mu=
sk ox</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vicu%C3%B1a" title=3D"V=
icu=C3=B1a">vicu=C3=B1a</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cat" =
title=3D"Cat">cat</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chiengora" =
title=3D"Chiengora">dog</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolf"=
 title=3D"Wolf">wolf</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angora_r=
abbit" title=3D"Angora rabbit">rabbit</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Bison" title=3D"Bison">bison</a>, or <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Chinchilla" title=3D"Chinchilla">chinchilla</a> hair, as well a=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkey_(bird)" title=3D"Turkey (=
bird)">turkey</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ostrich" titl=
e=3D"Ostrich">ostrich</a> feathers.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Synthetic_fibers">Synthetic=
 fibers</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Synthetic fiber=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synthetic_fiber" tit=
le=3D"Synthetic fiber">Synthetic fiber</a></div>
<p>Some examples of synthetic fibers that are used as yarn are <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nylon" title=3D"Nylon">nylon</a>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acrylic_fiber" title=3D"Acrylic fiber">acrylic=
 fiber</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rayon" title=3D"Rayon"=
>rayon</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyester" title=3D"Polyester">polyester</a>. Synthet=
ic fibers are generally extruded in continuous strands of gel-state materia=
ls. These strands are drawn (stretched), annealed (hardened), and cured to =
obtain properties desirable for later processing.
</p><p>Synthetic fibers come in three basic forms: staple, tow, and filamen=
t. Staple is cut fibers, generally sold in lengths up to 120&nbsp;mm. Tow i=
s a continuous "rope" of fibers consisting of many filaments loosely joined=
 side-to-side. Filament is a continuous strand consisting of anything from =
one filament to many. Synthetic fiber is most often <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Units_of_textile_measurement" title=3D"Units of textile m=
easurement">measured in a weight per linear measurement basis</a>, along wi=
th cut length. Denier and Dtex are the most common weight to length measure=
s. Cut-length only applies to staple fiber.
</p><p>Filament extrusion is sometimes referred to as "spinning," but most =
people equate spinning with spun yarn production.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Yarn_from_recycled_material=
s">Yarn from recycled materials</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit =
section: Yarn from recycled materials"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T-shirt" title=3D"T-shirt">T-sh=
irt</a> yarn is a recycled yarn made from the same fabric as is used in T-s=
hirts and other clothes. It is often made from the remainder fabric of clot=
hing manufacture, and therefore is considered a recycled and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environmentally_friendly" title=3D"Environmental=
ly friendly">eco-friendly</a> product. It can also be made at home out of u=
sed clothing.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-coburn_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-coburn-13"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The resulting yarn can be used in knit=
ted or crocheted items.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Comparison_of_material_prop=
erties">Comparison of material properties</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Comparison of material properties"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Restored_primary_level_spinning_machine_at_Qua=
rry_Bank_Mill.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload=
.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Restored_primary_level_spinning=
_machine_at_Quarry_Bank_Mill.jpg/250px-Restored_primary_level_spinning_mach=
ine_at_Quarry_Bank_Mill.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"143=
" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"480" data-file-height=3D"360=
"></a><figcaption>A fully restored Derby Doubler, winding a sliver lap read=
y for finisher carding at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quarry_B=
ank_Mill" title=3D"Quarry Bank Mill">Quarry Bank Mill</a> in the UK</figcap=
tion></figure>
<p>In general, natural fibers tend to require more careful handling than sy=
nthetics because they can shrink, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Felt" title=3D"Felt">felt</a>, stain, shed, fade, stretch, wrinkle, or be e=
aten by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moth" title=3D"Moth">moths=
</a> more readily, unless special treatments such as <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercerized_cotton" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mercer=
ized cotton">mercerization</a> or super washing are performed to strengthen=
, fix color, or otherwise enhance the fiber's own properties.
</p><p>Some types of protein yarns (i.e.,&nbsp;hair, silk, feathers) may fe=
el irritating to some people, causing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Contact_dermatitis" title=3D"Contact dermatitis">contact dermatitis</a>=
, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hives" title=3D"Hives">hives</a>=
, or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wheeze" title=3D"Wheeze">whee=
zing</a>. These reactions are likely a sensitivity to thicker and coarser f=
iber diameter or fiber ends.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In fac=
t, contrary to popular belief, wool allergies are practically unknown. Acco=
rding to a study reviewing the evidence of wool as an <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allergen" title=3D"Allergen">allergen</a> conducted by =
Acta Dermato-Venereologica,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-pmid28350041_17-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-pmid2835=
0041-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> contemporary superfine or ultrafine Merino wool with t=
heir reduced fibre diameters do not provoke itch, are well tolerated and in=
 fact benefit <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dermatitis" title=3D=
"Dermatitis">eczema</a> management.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-pmid28350041_17-1" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-=
pmid28350041-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Further studies suggest that known allergens a=
pplied during textile processing are minimally present in wool garments tod=
ay given current industry practices and are unlikely to lead to allergic re=
actions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>When natural hair-type fibers are burned, they tend to singe and hav=
e a smell of burnt hair; this is because many, like human hair, are protein=
-derived. Cotton and viscose (rayon) yarns burn as a wick. Synthetic yarns =
generally tend to melt, though some synthetics are inherently <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fire-retardant_fabric" title=3D"Fire-retardant =
fabric">flame-retardant</a>. Noting how an unidentified fiber strand burns =
and smells can assist in determining if it is natural or synthetic, and wha=
t the fiber content is.
</p><p>Both synthetic and natural yarns can <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Pill_(textile)" title=3D"Pill (textile)">pill</a>. Pilling is a f=
unction of fiber content, spinning method, twist, contiguous staple length,=
 and fabric construction. Single ply yarns or using fibers like merino wool=
 are known to pill more due to the fact that in the former, the single ply =
is not tight enough to securely retain all the fibers under abrasion, and t=
he merino wool's short staple length allows the ends of the fibers to pop o=
ut of the twist more easily.
</p><p>Yarns combining synthetic and natural fibers inherit the properties =
of each parent, according to the proportional composition. Synthetics are a=
dded to lower cost, increase durability, add unusual color or visual effect=
s, provide machine washability and stain resistance, reduce heat retention,=
 or lighten garment weight.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Structure">Structure</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Structure"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinning_(textiles)"=
 title=3D"Spinning (textiles)">Spinning (textiles)</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Spinning_jenny.jpg" class=3D"m=
w-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm=
ons/thumb/8/87/Spinning_jenny.jpg/250px-Spinning_jenny.jpg" decoding=3D"asy=
nc" width=3D"250" height=3D"206" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"705" data-file-height=3D"582"></a><figcaption>A <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Spinning_jenny" title=3D"Spinning jenny">Spinning Jenny</=
a>, spinning machine which was significant in the beginning of the Industri=
al Revolution</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Yarn_twist_S-Left_Z-Right.png" class=3D"mw-fi=
le-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/=
thumb/2/25/Yarn_twist_S-Left_Z-Right.png/250px-Yarn_twist_S-Left_Z-Right.pn=
g" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"236" class=3D"mw-file-element=
" data-file-width=3D"263" data-file-height=3D"326"></a><figcaption>S- and Z=
-twist yarn</figcaption></figure>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Spun_yarn"><span class=3D"a=
nchor" id=3D"Spun_yarn"></span>Spun yarn</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=
=3D"Edit section: Spun yarn"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Spun yarn is made by twisting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
taple_(textiles)" title=3D"Staple (textiles)">staple</a> <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibre" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fibre">fibres<=
/a> together to make a cohesive thread, or "single".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_not=
e-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Twisting fibres into yarn in the process called <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinning_(textiles)" title=3D"Spinning (t=
extiles)">spinning</a> can be dated back to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Upper_Paleolithic" title=3D"Upper Paleolithic">Upper Paleolit=
hic</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
0<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and yarn spinning was one =
of the first processes to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indus=
trialized" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Industrialized">industrialized</a=
>. Spun yarns are produced by placing a series of individual fibres or fila=
ments together to form a continuous assembly of overlapping fibres, usually=
 bound together by twist. Spun yarns may contain a single type of fibre, or=
 be a blend of various types. Combining synthetic fibres (which can have hi=
gh strength, lustre, and fire retardant qualities) with natural fibres (whi=
ch have good water absorbency and skin comforting qualities) is very common=
. The most widely used blends are cotton-polyester and wool-acrylic fibre b=
lends. Blends of different natural fibres are common too, especially with m=
ore expensive fibres such as alpaca, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Angora_wool" title=3D"Angora wool">angora</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Cashmere_wool" title=3D"Cashmere wool">cashmere</a>.
</p><p>Yarn is selected for different textiles based on the characteristics=
 of the yarn fibres, such as warmth (wool), light weight (cotton or rayon),=
 durability (nylon is added to sock yarn, for example), or softness (cashme=
re, alpaca).
</p><p>Yarn is composed of twisted strands of fiber, which are known as pli=
es when grouped together.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These str=
ands of yarn are twisted together (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Plying" title=3D"Plying">plied</a>) in the opposite direction to make a th=
icker yarn. Depending on the direction of this final twist, the yarn will h=
ave either <i>s-twist</i> (the threads appear to go "up" to the left) or <i=
>z-twist</i> (to the right). For a single ply yarn, the direction of the fi=
nal twist is the same as its original twist. The twist direction of yarn ca=
n affect the final properties of the fabric, and combined use of the two tw=
ist directions can nullify skewing in knitted fabric.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_no=
te-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The mechanical integrity of yarn is derived from frictional contacts=
 between its composing fibers. The science behind this was first studied by=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galileo" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Galileo">Galileo</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Carded_and_combed_yarn">Car=
ded and combed yarn</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DYarn&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Car=
ded and combed yarn"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Combed yarns are produced by adding another step of yarn spinning, namel=
y combing, which aligns the fibres and removes the short fibres carried ove=
r from the previous step of carding. Combed yarn results in superior-qualit=
y fabrics. In comparison to carded yarns, this particular yarn is slightly =
more expensive, because the weaving is a long, consuming process. Combing s=
eparates small fibres from elongated fibres, in which this procedure makes =
the yarn softer and smoother.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Hosiery_yarn">Hosiery yarn<=
/h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Hosiery yarn"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Hosiery yarns are used in the manufacturing of <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Knitted_fabric" title=3D"Knitted fabric">knitted fabrics</a=
>. Since the knitted materials are more delicate than woven materials; henc=
e hosiery yarns are made 'softer' with fewer <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Twist_per_inch" title=3D"Twist per inch">twists per inch</a> tha=
n their woven counterparts. Hosiery yarn comes from a separate spinning pro=
cess (melt spinning), and is used with circular knitting machines to form f=
abric.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-26">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Open-end_yarn">Open-end yar=
n</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Open-end yarn"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Open-end yarn is produced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Op=
en-end_spinning" title=3D"Open-end spinning">open-end spinning</a> without =
a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spindle_(textiles)" title=3D"Spi=
ndle (textiles)">spindle</a>. The method of spinning is different from <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_spinning" title=3D"Ring spinning"=
>ring spinning</a>. In open-end yarn, there is no <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Roving" title=3D"Roving">roving</a> frame stage. <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sliver_(textiles)" title=3D"Sliver (textiles=
)">Sliver</a> from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carding" ti=
tle=3D"Carding">card</a> goes into the rotor, is spun into yarn directly. O=
pen-end yarn can be produced from short fibers. Open-end yarns are differen=
t from ring yarns. Open-end yarns are limited to coarser counts.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Y=
arn#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Novelty_yarn">Novelty yarn<=
/h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Novelty yarn"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Novelty_yarns" title=
=3D"Novelty yarns">Novelty yarns</a></div>
<p>Novelty yarns or complex yarns are yarns with special (fancy) effects in=
troduced during spinning or plying. One example is <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Slub_(textiles)" title=3D"Slub (textiles)">slub</a> yarns,=
 yarn with thick or thin sections alternating regularly or irregularly. In =
a similar manner, creating deliberate unevenness, additions or injections o=
f neps or metallic or synthetic fibers (along with natural fibers) in spinn=
ing creates novelty yarns.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Filament_yarn">Filament yar=
n</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Filament yarn"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Filament yarn consists of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Filam=
ent_fibre" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Filament fibre">filament fibres</=
a> (very long continuous fibres) either twisted together or only grouped to=
gether. Thicker <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monofilament_line"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Monofilament line">monofilaments</a> are ty=
pically used for industrial purposes rather than fabric production or decor=
ation. Silk is a natural filament, and synthetic filament yarns are used to=
 produce silk-like effects.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Texturized_yarn">Texturized=
 yarn</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Texturized yarn">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<p>Texturized yarns are made by a process of air texturizing filament yarns=
 (sometimes referred to as <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tasl=
anizing" title=3D"Taslanizing">taslanizing</a></i>), which combines multipl=
e filament yarns into a yarn with some of the characteristics of spun yarns=
. They are synthetic continuous filaments that are modified to impart speci=
al texture and appearance. It was originally applied to synthetic fibers to=
 reduce transparency, slipperiness and increase warmth, absorbency and make=
s the yarn more opaque. It was used to manufacture a variety of textile pro=
ducts: knitted underwear and outer wear, shape-retaining knitted suits, ove=
rcoats. They also were used in the production of artificial fur, carpets, b=
lankets, etc.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-30=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_no=
te-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Colour">Colour</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3Dedit&a=
mp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: Colour"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Yarn_store_with_various_yarns=
.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.or=
g/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Yarn_store_with_various_yarns.jpg/250px-Yarn=
_store_with_various_yarns.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"1=
88" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"4032" data-file-height=3D"=
3024"></a><figcaption>Yarn in various colours sold at a yarn store</figcapt=
ion></figure>
<p>Yarn may be used undyed, or may be coloured with <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_dye" title=3D"Natural dye">natural</a> or artific=
ial <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dye" title=3D"Dye">dyes</a>. M=
ost yarns have a single uniform hue, but there is also a wide selection of =
variegated yarns:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heather_(fabric)" title=3D=
"Heather (fabric)">Heathered</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Tweed" title=3D"Tweed">tweed</a>: yarn with flecks of different coloured =
fibre</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ombr%C3%A9" title=3D"Ombr=C3=
=A9">Ombr=C3=A9</a>: variegated yarn with light and dark shades of a single=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hue" title=3D"Hue">hue</a></li>
<li>Multicoloured: variegated yarn with two or more distinct hues (a "parro=
t colourway" might have green, yellow and red)</li>
<li>Self-striping: yarn dyed with lengths of colour that will automatically=
 create stripes in a knitted or crocheted object</li>
<li>Marled: yarn made from strands of different-coloured yarn twisted toget=
her, sometimes in closely related hues</li></ul>
<p>Each of these different colours and styles are achieved through a proces=
s called yarn dyeing. There are many different methods of yarn dyeing: pack=
age dyeing, skein dyeing, space dyeing, warp beam dyeing, and more.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Yarn#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Package Dyeing: This is the most commonly used method. This is when=
 yarn is already spun up in bulk and then lowered into a chamber filled wit=
h dye. When the yarn is done absorbing the dye, it is removed from the cyli=
ndrical chamber to dry.</li>
<li>Skein Dyeing: This is the process of when yarn is laid loosely in skein=
s or hanks. They are then laid on top of a bar and submerged into what is c=
alled a dyebath.</li>
<li>Space Dyeing: This method is used to achieve the multi-colored effect. =
This method is achieved by taking sections of yarn and dipping them into di=
fferent colours. After dipping one section into a colour, a chemical called=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mordant" title=3D"Mordant">mordan=
t</a> is used to permanently keep that color on the yarn so that the next c=
olor will not bleed into the prior color.</li>
<li>Warp Beam Dyeing: This is a larger version of package dyeing; however, =
it is only used in the manufacture of woven fabrics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_not=
e-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup></li></ul>
