<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Weight">Weight</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3Dedit&a=
mp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: Weight"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn_weight" title=
=3D"Yarn weight">Yarn weight</a></div>
<p>Yarn quantities for handcrafts are usually measured and sold by weight i=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ounce" title=3D"Ounce">ounces</a=
> (oz) or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gram" title=3D"Gram">gra=
ms</a> (g). Common sizes include 25g, 50g, and 100g skeins. Some companies =
also primarily measure in ounces with common sizes being three-ounce, four-=
ounce, six-ounce, and eight-ounce skeins. Textile measurements are taken at=
 a standard temperature and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Humidi=
ty" title=3D"Humidity">humidity</a> because variations in heat and humidity=
 can cause fibers to absorb different amounts of moisture from the air, thu=
s increasing the measured weight of the yarn without adding any fiber mater=
ial. The actual length of the yarn contained in a ball or skein can vary du=
e to the inherent heaviness of the fibre and the thickness of the strand; f=
or instance, a 50&nbsp;g skein of lace weight mohair may contain several hu=
ndred metres, while a 50&nbsp;g skein of bulky wool may contain only 60 met=
res.
</p><p>Craft yarn comes in several thicknesses or weights. This is not to b=
e confused with the measurement and weight listed above. The Craft Yarn Cou=
ncil of America promotes a standardized industry system for measuring yarn =
weight, where weights are numbered from 0 (finest) to 7 (thickest).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Yarn#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Each weight can be described by a number =
and name: Size 0 yarn is called Lace, size 1 is Super Fine, size 2 is Fine,=
 size 3 is Light, size 4 is Medium, size 5 is Bulky, size 6 is Super Bulky,=
 and size 7 is Jumbo.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_34-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-:1-34"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Each weight also has several commonly used but unregulated terms ass=
ociated with it. However, this naming convention is more descriptive than p=
recise; fibre artists disagree about where on the continuum each lies, and =
the precise relationships between the sizes. These terms include: fingering=
, sport, double-knit (or DK), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wors=
ted" title=3D"Worsted">worsted</a>, aran (or heavy worsted), bulky, super-b=
ulky, and roving.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_34-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-:1-34"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Another measurement of yarn weight, often used by weavers, is wraps =
per inch (WPI). The yarn is wrapped snugly around a ruler and the number of=
 wraps that fit in an inch are counted.
</p><p>Labels on yarn for handicrafts often include information on <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gauge_(knitting)" title=3D"Gauge (knittin=
g)">gauge</a>, which can also help determine yarn weight. Gauge, known in t=
he UK as tension, is a measurement of how many stitches and rows are produc=
ed per inch or per cm on a specified size of knitting needle or crochet hoo=
k. The proposed standardization uses a four-by-four inch/ten-by-ten cm knit=
ted stockinette or single crocheted square, with the resultant number of st=
itches across and rows high made by the suggested tools on the label to det=
ermine the gauge.
</p><p>In Europe, textile engineers often use the unit <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tex_(unit)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tex (unit)"=
>tex</a>, which is the weight in grams of a kilometre of yarn, or decitex, =
which is a finer measurement corresponding to the weight in grams of 10&nbs=
p;km of yarn. Many other units have been used over time by different indust=
ries.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Yarn_skeins">Yarn skeins</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Yarn skeins"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There are many different ways in which yarn is wound, including hanks, s=
keins, donut balls, cakes, and cones.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Hank">Hank</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Hank"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A hank<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> of yarn is a looped bundl=
e of yarn,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_36-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-:0-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> similar to how w=
ire is typically sold. The yarn is usually tied in two places directly oppo=
site each other to keep the loops together and to keep them from tangling. =
Hanks are a preferred method of fastening yarn for many yarn sellers and ya=
rn-dyers due to its ability to more widely display the qualities of the fib=
er.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_36-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-:0-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is often wound using=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swift_(textiles)" title=3D"Swif=
t (textiles)">swift</a>, a standing contraption that holds a yarn hank with=
out obstruction and spins on a central axis to facilitate yarn ball winding=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> There are two subtypes of hanks: t=
wisted and folded. A twisted hank is a hank that has been twisted into a ro=
pe braid. A folded hank is a hank that has been folded in half and wrapped =
in a label for retail purposes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_36-2" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-:0-36"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Skein">Skein</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Skein"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Skeins are one of the most common types of yarn ball. Although skeins ar=
e technically described as yarn that has been wound into an oblong shape, t=
he word "skein" is used generically to describe any ball of yarn.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-:0_36-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Yarn#cite_note-:0-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Many large-scale yarn retailers like=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lion_Brand_Yarns" title=3D"Lion B=
rand Yarns">Lion brand</a> and parent companies like Yarnspirations sell th=
eir yarn in skeins. Unlike other types of yarn balls, a skein allows you to=
 access both ends of the yarn.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_36-4" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-:0-36"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> The yarn end in the inside of the skein is called a center pull.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-:0_36-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-:0-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> One major complaint of center pul=
l bullet skeins is that the inside yarn end is not easily found, and often =
is pulled out of the skein in a jumble of tangled yarn called "yarn barf". =
There are two types of skeins: a pull skein, which is more rectangular in s=
hape, and a bullet skein, which is rounder.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_36-6" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-:0=
-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yarn#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"British_standard_yarn_measu=
res">British standard yarn measures</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DYarn&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"E=
dit section: British standard yarn measures"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
